I recently went to look for a decent Ethernet switch that we can use for the robot, given that the well reviewed Brainboxes switch is not readily available in Canada and is rather pricey compared to other options (likely because they are shipped from the US).

And it seems I have found a good candidate on AliExpress: https://www.aliexpress.com/item/1005006447336886.html 20240209_122710.resized 2040Ã—1530 81.9 KB 20240209_122726.resized 2040Ã—1530 88 KB 20240209_122836.resized 2040Ã—1530 65.8 KB

It checks almost all the boxes: Wide input voltage range : 5V - 58V, I did a quick test and it was happy doing its full 100Mbit/s down to 4.6V Rugged : It has an aluminium case Mounts easily to the robot : It has a DIN Rail mount. The two screws holding the DIN Rail mount can be removed and the screw holes can be used to mount the switch directly to something else.

As for compliance with R611 (i.e. will it conduct GND to the frame via the metal case): My multimeter does not measure any continuity between V- and the case. There is continuity between the GND post on the case and the GND post on the terminal. This continuity is gone when I remove the front panel that surrounds the Ethernet ports.

Weâ€™ll see how this holds up over the next few days being mounted to the robot. Iâ€™ll keep you posted.

At the time of writing this, the switch cost CAD 14.05 (or USD 10.20) including shipping to Canada. Thatâ€™s cheaper than almost all 5 Port switches I can get on Amazon.ca.

posts.cooked:
Itâ€™s probably fine.

The argument is that a single qualification match costs hundreds of dollars ($300-600) in registration fees and you are saving $50 on a component between your radio and your Rio.

Thatâ€™s a good point.

So far I havenâ€™t gotten the feeling that there is a lack of quality with this device. I will continue testing, because I think there is value in knowing the options. I do agree that as soon as we have the new radio with the extra Ethernet ports additional switches should be obsolete. Iâ€™m always for keeping complexity down for things to remain manageable.

Just wanted to provide an end of season update from our end.

It worked absolutely flawlessly during the 2024 season (3 events) with multiple massive hits we took that bent our frame badly (twice!) and even nearly cut through some motor wires (we lost our arm motors in that one ). The switch was mounted directly to a metal plate on the frame using the screw holes where the DIN rail bracket was mounted initially. The only issue we had with continuity from frame to ground was because of a SparkMAX housing being somehow shorted to ground ( of which we, anecdotally, went through 4 more of at one event ). We powered the switch off a 12V 500ma port on a VRM (not that it needed it, but it was the closest thing available). It had our Limelight, OrangePi, roboRIO and the radio (via the RPM ) plugged into it. The fifth port was used to connect to the robot, which worked much better than the second port on our radio. Weâ€™ll probably not need it from next season on with the new radio having more ports available, but may use it still if our radio mounting position isnâ€™t conducive to running more than one Ethernet wire there.

I did open it up to make sure the PCB wouldnâ€™t start rubbing against the case and start randomly conducting. Iâ€™d like to think I have above average experience with embedded hardware like this for someone who is merely a software engineer, so I was quite interested as well . That happens when you start dabbling in Embedded Linux development as a hobby.

You can actually buy the bare module here: https://www.aliexpress.com/item/1005005683127216.html That should have some decent pictures of what it looks like. The PCB held by sliding into groves on the inside of the aluminum case (the silver strips on either side of the PCB roughly indicate where it sits in the groves). And then itâ€™s all held in place by the front and back plates and a screw at the bottom. Iâ€™ll take some pictures when Iâ€™m back with the robot (weâ€™re currently on a two week break to allow students to catch up with tests and whatnot).

Near the power terminals you can see the three blue metal-oxide varistors (one for V+, V- and GND) that give this thing itâ€™s 4kV surge protection rating.

Whoâ€™s ready for round 2 of Felix orders random industrial switches from AliExpress?

Our last one (seen in the initial post in this thread) has served us very well last season. We still use it today and will use it on our competition robot for the 2025 season.

For our 7200 goes Germany project (which happens at the same time the ONT Provincials will be) we needed another switch like this and I took another look around.

Highlights:

Two power inputs for redundancy (7-60V)

P1- and P2- have continuity

Most importantly: No continuity between any of the power inputs and the GND screw/case/DIN rail mount. So it should be safe for FRC use.

Gigabit performance
